Minimalist zen garden viewed from above, featuring perfectly raked white sand with precise curved line patterns, a single smooth dark stone positioned off-center, and one small bonsai tree casting a soft shadow. The composition emphasizes negative space and simplicity. Subtle warm afternoon light creates gentle gradients across the sand ripples. The aesthetic evokes Japanese wabi-sabi philosophy with intentional imperfection and restrained elegance. Clean geometric divisions suggest structured simplicity, with the vast empty sand representing stripped-down functionality while the few carefully placed elements represent essential features. Muted earth tones with cream, charcoal gray, and soft moss green. Shot from a high angle with shallow depth of field blurring the garden's edges.
